      <T n="text">0xD9DC6357<!--Ever feel like your Sims just wake up on the wrong side of the bed? <font color="#199C2C"><b>Luck</b></font> changes daily and can affect various things in a Sim’s daily life. Some of the things impacted by Luck are:\n• Career progression\n• Crafting and Cooking results (beware of fire!)\n• Foraging finds\n• Collectibles\n• Gnome relations\n…and more!\n\nIf you'd prefer for fate and the cosmos to mind its own business, opt out of Luck by going to the Main Menu and selecting <font color="#199C2C"><b>Game Options > Pack Settings</b></font> and find the toggle for <font color="#199C2C"><b>Enable Luck</b></font>.--></T>
    </U>
    <U>
      <T n="image" p="InEP19\UI\Tutorial\EP19_Luck_Slide2.png">2f7d0004:00000000:43a65b04a276ee9c</T>
      <T n="text">0xBCA82DD2<!--However, Sims do not need to sit back and let Luck change on them each day. Ways to change Luck include but aren’t limited to:\n• Getting help from the Garden Pal, Spruce Almighty—Summon them at the <font color="#199C2C"><b>Glasswood Tree</b></font> in Sprucederry Grove.\n• Appeal to the Great Gnome on the Coast of Adhmor.\n• Foraging, crafting at the <font color="#199C2C"><b>Apothecary Table</b></font>, or purchasing a <font color="#199C2C"><b>Freezer Bunny Foot</b></font> for better luck.\n• Foraging, crafting at the <font color="#199C2C"><b>Apothecary Table</b></font>, or purchasing a <font color="#199C2C"><b>Cowplant Horn</b></font> for worse luck.--></T>
    </U>
  </L>
